<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Functions Learning Plan 3</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Quadratic &amp; Power Functions</P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>While working through this plan you should be referring to your lecture notes titled ‘Functions’.</P>

<P>In the previous plan it was shown that business problems could be modelled by linear functions.   Unfortunately many problems cannot be modelled by a linear relationship.   Remember that a linear function either rises, drops or remains constant over its range.   Linear functions are known as monotonic.   If they start to increase or decrease they will continue to do so monotonously.</P>

<P>Profits, revenues and unit costs are all capable of changing direction over any given range of sales or output values.   For this reason we must provide additional mathematical functions which will allow non-linear behaviour to be modelled satisfactorily.</P>

<B><P>Quadratic Functions</P>

</B><P>A quadratic function can normally be distinguished from a linear function by the addition of a term containing x<SUP>2</SUP>.  It can be written in the general form</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">f(x) = ax<SUP>2</SUP> + bx + c</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">where a, b and c are constant terms known as coefficients.</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>In this general form the graph of a quadratic function will normally be a u-shaped or n-shaped curve.   The specific shape of the curve is ultimately determined by the values of a, b and c.   In particular if a &gt; 0 then the curve is u-shaped, if a &lt; 0 then the curve is n-shaped.</P>

<P>Consider the quadratic function discussed on page 4 of your notes.</P>
<B>
<P>Example </P>
</B>
